class Solution:
    def canSplitArray(self, nums: List[int], m: int) -> bool:
        n = len(nums)

        prefix = [0]
        for num in nums:
            prefix.append(prefix[-1] + num)

        @cache
        def dp(i, j):
            if i == j:
                return False
            if j - i == 1:
                return True
            for k in range(i+1, j):
                if dp(i, k) and dp(k, j) and (prefix[k] - prefix[i] >= m or k - i == 1) and (prefix[j] - prefix[k] >= m or j - k == 1):
                    return True
            return False

        return dp(0, n)
```

This implements a memoized dynamic programming solution. The dp function checks if it is possible to split the subarray nums[i:j] into valid subarrays by trying all possible splits at index k. The prefix sum array is precomputed to quickly check if the split subarrays satisfy the sum criteria. Overall this runs in O(n^3) time and O(n^2) space.

