class Solution:
    def backspaceCompare(self, s: str, t: str) -> bool:
        i, j = len(s) - 1, len(t) - 1
        skipS, skipT = 0, 0

        while i >= 0 or j >= 0:
            while i >= 0:
                if s[i] == '#':
                    skipS += 1
                    i -= 1
                elif skipS > 0:
                    skipS -= 1
                    i -= 1
                else:
                    break

            while j >= 0:
                if t[j] == '#':
                    skipT += 1
                    j -= 1
                elif skipT > 0:
                    skipT -= 1
                    j -= 1
                else:
                    break

            if i >= 0 and j >= 0:
                if s[i] != t[j]:
                    return False
            elif i >= 0 or j >= 0:
                return False

            i -= 1
            j -= 1

        return True
```

The key points are:

- Process strings s and t from back to front using indices i and j
- Use skipS and skipT variables to track number of characters to skip due to backspaces
- Increment skip when '#' is found, decrement when skipping, break when no more skipping 
- Compare s[i] and t[j] only when no skips are left
- Return False if any char mismatch or if indices don't reach 0 together

This traverses each string only once, using O(1) extra space.

